definition: to rise/to raise/to get up/to set out/to start/to appear/to launch/to initiate (action)/to draft/to establish/to get (from a depot or counter)/verb suffix, to start/starting from (a time, place, price etc)/classifier for occurrences or unpredictable events: case, instance/classifier for groups: batch, group

sentences.english: Some arise from common law. Others are statutory.
sentences.chinese: 它們有些源起於普通法，其他則是屬於成文法。

sentences.english: The European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) originated from the acceptability of sovereignties in the European Community(EC).
sentences.chinese: 歐洲經貨聯盟源起於歐共體各主權國家的合意。

sentences.english: Fan vaults, springing from slender columns or pendants, became popular.
sentences.chinese: 源起於細長園柱或懸垂裝飾的扇形拱頂，變得普及。

sentences.english: Symbolic exchange theory originated from George Bataille' s concept of expending and Marcel Mauss' s gift exchange theory.
sentences.chinese: 象徵交換源起於巴塔耶的花費觀念和莫斯的禮物交換。

sentences.english: Chateaubriand's three romances of America are situated in the farther south.
sentences.chinese: 更多勃里昂寫的三部美國傳奇源起遙遠的南方。

sentences.english: The Old Testament Passover celebration began the night the Israelites left Egypt.
sentences.chinese: 舊約裏，守逾越節源起於以色列人離開埃及當晚。

definition: lit. floating wine goblets on a stream/the origin (of some phenomenon)
to trace sth back to its origin
to pursue sth back to its origins/to trace back to the source/to get to the bottom of sth
(of watercourses) source and direction of flow/origin and development
traceable to the same stock (idiom); of a common origin (of trends, ideas etc)
